This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with the annotation of temporal order of events in text. It also involves the development of new annotation schemes and tools for annotation and adjudication, which are relevant to natural language processing. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the annotation scheme and tools involve the use of commonsense reasoning strategies, which are relevant to AI. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category as the paper involves the development of new strategies for encoding vagueness in temporal relations, which could be relevant to machine learning algorithms. 

cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is a possible sub-category as the paper involves the annotation of a fiction corpus, which could be relevant to information retrieval tasks such as text classification and recommendation. 

Finally, cs.CY (Computers and Society) is a less likely sub-category as the paper involves the development of new annotation tools, which could have implications for the ethical and social aspects of natural language processing.
